    <h1 class="opener__hed  -is-over-bg opener__hed--light opener__hed--small" >        An 11-Year-Old Denied Making a Threat and Was Allowed to Return to School. Tennessee Police Arrested Him Anyway.
    </h1>

    
            <div class="article-meta-1  -is-over-bg article-meta-1--light">
            <span class="article-meta-1__byline">
                by <a class="name" href="https://www.propublica.org/people/aliyya-swaby">Aliyya Swaby</a>, ProPublica, and <span class="name">Paige Pfleger</span>, WPLN/Nashville Public Radio            </span>
            <time class="article-meta-1__pubdate">
                <time class="timestamp" datetime="2024-10-30EDT07:00">Oct. 30, 7 a.m. EDT</time>
            </time>
        </div>
    
    </div> <!-- Close .opener__topic-title-dek-wrapper -->

            <div class="content"> <!-- not sure if this is the best way to reestablish the text column -->
            <h2 class="opener__dek opener__dek--match-text-column" style="display: none">                A state law makes threats of mass violence at school a felony, even if they’re not credible. Judges and school officials say the law unnecessarily traumatizes kids.
            </h2>
        </div>
    
</div>
        
<div class="article-meta-1
     article-meta-1--left      article-meta-1--hide-byline " data-pp-location="article meta">

